{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_broadwick_ver01/data/sn93065779/00279558236/1946020701/0640.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE SIX\nFARM NEWS\nIt\u2019s Bedtime For\nN.C. Sweet Potatoes\nIt\u2019s almost bedtime for this year\u2019s\ncrop of sweet potatoes in North\nCarolina and horticulturists of the\nState College Extension Service,\nanxious to avoid a repeat on the\npoor quality crop of last year, have\noutlined a number of suggestions to\ngrowers.\nYields on the state\u2019s 80,000 acres\nof sweet potatoes in 1945 averaged\nbetween 97 and 115 bushels per acre\nbut quality was poor and returns\ncorrespondingly discouraging. Now.\nhowever, demand for potatoes con\ntinues strong on the Southern mar\nkets and buyers from Virginia, Geor\ngia and South Carolina are frequent\ning markets in Davidson and other\ncounties. Curb market reports have\nindicated that people will buy good\npotatoes with little regard for prices\nwhile passing up poor grades irre\nspective of how low the price.\nThese suggestions have been of\nfered to Tar Heel growers:\nBuy certified seed stock now\n(about $4 a bushel); if old bed is to\nbe used, renew it now; remove all\nold dirt and disinfect the area, al\nlowing bed to air several days.\nRound up equipment for electric or\nflue-heated beds.\nIf possible avoid the use of ma\nnure as a source of hotbed heat be\ncause manure has been found to\ncause or spread disease in the bed.\nMore sweet potato plants can be\nobtained per bushel of seed bedded\nif electric or fire-heated beds are\nused.\nPastures To Take\nBig Postwar Role\nIn the face of predictions by farm\nleaders that North Carolina agricul\nture is about to enter an era of\nmechanization in which hay, small\ngrains and pastures will be given\nconsiderably more attention than in\nthe past, far-sighted recommenda\ntions have been made for the seed\ning of permanent pastures in War\nren and surrounding counties.\nThe Warren County Agricultural\nCouncil, combining the reported ex\nperiences of farmers with the results\nof intensive research, has released\nthe following recommended mixture\nper acre for seeding permanent pas\ntures, with the first figure following\neach seed type indicating the num\nber of pounds of seed to be used on\npoorer soils, the second figure indi\ncating the number of pounds on me\ndium to good soils::\nOrchard Grass, 10 and 8; Red Top]\n(Herds) Grass, 6 and 7; White!\nDutch Clover, 3 and 3; Dallis Grass, I\n5 and 5; Lespedeza (either Kobe or j\nKorean), 20 and 15.\nBetter pastures will result, the I\ncouncil says, if the orchard grass,\nRed Top and White Dutch clover are\nsown in September or October, with I\nDallis Grass and lespedeza to be\nseeded late in February or early\nMarch. If conditions are such that j\nseeding can not take place in the\nFall, all varieties should be mixed!\nand sown in February or March, j\nFertilizer recommendations include:\n400 pounds of 18 per cent superphos- j\nphate and 100 pounds of mmate of j\npotash per acre with one ton of j\nlimestone at planting. If commer\ncial fertilizer is used instead, the\nrecommendation is: 400 to 600\npounds of 0-14-7 or 0-12-12.\nThis pasture plan meets the 1946\nAAA requirements.\nHogs need to be treated for lice\nduring the winter months because\nthe lice may he carriers of swine\npox.\n\u201cI had a tough battle to get into\nsociety.\u201d\n\u201cHad to keep your chin up, eh?\u201d\n\u201cNo, just my nose.\u201d\nOLIVER\nCost-Reducing\nFARM EQUIPMENT\nSALES AND SERVICE\nGeneral Line of Hardware.\nAbernethy Equipment\nCompany\nPhone 288-W. Charlotte Hwy.\nN. C. FIRST GRADE\nGAS 20 GALLON\nLET US RECAP YOUR TIRES\nTHE FAMOUS \u201cBACON\u201d WAY.\nWe Also Do Section Repair Work.\nMcGinnis bros.\nPHONE 382\nDan McGinnis\u2014Vaughn McGinnis\nDr. Aubrey L. Palmer\nCharlotte Optometrist\nIn Lincolnton each Thursday 9 a. m. to 5 p. m.\nLincolnton Office\u2014\nCharlotte Office\u2014\nEYES EXAMINED GLASSES FITTED\nState College Hints\nTo Farm Homemakers\nBy RUTH CURRENT\nNorth Carolina State College\nCitrus fruits rolling into markets\nfrom this year\u2019s good crop bring\nwealth of vitamin C, nutritionally\nspeaking. Since sugar is still tight\nly rationed, oranges and tangerines\nrate a welcome for the help they\noffer in the \u201csomething sweet\u201d line.\nWhile most people know that or\nange juice is a high-powered drink\nfor vitamin C. nutritionists say that\nall of the familiar citrus fruits are\nbountiful sources of this vitamin. A\nhalf-glass (4 ounces) of orange or\ngrapefruit juice will go far toward\nsupplying a day\u2019s needs of vitamin\nC. So will half a grapefruit, or a\nwhole orange, or a couple of tanger\nines or lemons.\nBecause pulp, as well as juice,\ncontains vitamin C, there is vitamin\nthrift in serving juice unstrained,\nand even higher vitamin economy in\neating citrus fruit simply halved,\nsliced, or sectioned.\nSo destructive are heat and air to\nvitamin C in cut or juiced fruit that\nthe vitamin-thrifty homemaker takes\nspecial care to keep them under con\ntrol. To this end, the nutritionists\nadvise cutting or slicing citrus fruit\nas near as possible to serving time.\nIf breakfast citrus juice is squeez\ned the night before as a time-saver,\nkeep it cold and covered, remember\ning that the less air space there is\nbetween juice and container top, the\nbetter for vitamin C. With these\nprecautions, citrus juice will lose lit\ntle of its most valuable vitamin, even\nif stored for 24 hours.\nBesides serving as sweets, oranges\nand tangerines have possibilities as\nsweeteners. Home economists sug\ngest, for example: In orange gelatin\ndessert, if orange sections are used.\nin addition to orange juice, sugar\ncalled for may be reduced a third\nor even a half. And for those who\nlike a sweet salad, orange bits or\nslices mixed with slaw or combined\nwith grated carrot provide the touch\nof sweetness without rationed sugar.\nThe fit of a slip depends not only\non its size but also on its cut, cloth\ning specialists remind us. Bias-cut\nslips, sold so widely in stores, usu\nally fit slender figures but straight\ncut slips are better suited to stoot\nfigures and large hips. Straight-cut\nslips stay down better over the knees\nwhen sitting and are less likely to\nhang unevenly and \"cut under\u201d at\nthe back, which gives an especially\nurgly appearance with sheer dresses.\nWhat makes for a good buy in\nsheets holds also for a good buy in\nj pillow-cases\u2014firm weave, little siz\ning, torn length, smooth and even\nj hems.\nI A word about sizes: Pillow-cases\ntoo large wrinkle under the head.\nI Cases too small bunch up the pillow\ninto a hard lump and are likely to\nb e strained. Your best bet is a case\n1 1/2 inches wider and 6 inches long\ner than the pillow.\nWhen you buy bath towels you\nmust sometimes compromise between\ndurability and drying power. A tow\nel that dries well is soft, fluffy, has\nlittle twist in the pile yarns, and a\nloose foundation. So look for a towel\nwith a firm foundation and soft\nloops, about 1 8-inch long, rather\nthan close together, but not too tight\nly twisted.\nOther earmarks of a good towel:\nFirm selvages with the crosswise\nyarns securely wrapped around the\nlengthwise or warp yarns; hems at\nleast 3/8 to 1 inch wide with 1/4\ninch or more of a raw edge turned\nunder; color-fastness.\nWhite spots on varnished furni\nture may be caused by standing wa\nter, hot dishes or alcohol, according\nto wood experts and furnishings\nspecialists.\nIf the spots are slight, they may\nbe removed simply by rubbing with\ncamphorated oil or oil of pepper\nmint get 10c worth at the drug\nstore. Or they may disappear when\nthe surface of the furniture is wash\ned with a mixture of 1 quart of\nwarm tvater; 3 tablespoons of boiled\nlinseed oil, and 1 tablespoon of tur\npentine; then dried with a soft dry\ncloth, and rubbed with furniture\npolish.\nFor more severe white spots a\nmixture that may be used is salt and\nsalad oil. Dip the finger in oil, then\nin salt, and rub. Repeat until the\nspot disappears. Then dry and pol\nish. Or use a paste made of pow\ndered pumice and linseed oil, and\nrub over the spot with the finger\nor soft cloth until the spot disap\npears. Don\u2019t rub too hard you\nmight remove the varnish.\nA good tailor does not press wool\ncompletely dry, for it scorches very\neasily. Rather, he lifts the wool gar\nment from the pressing board while\nthe last bit of steam is still rising\nfrom it. Then he pats or beats out\nthat little whiff of steam with his\nTHE LINCOLN TIMES, LINCOLNTON, N. C\u201e THURSDAY, FEB. 7, 1946\nFARMERS PROTEST\nAGAINST STRIKE\n1\nWashington, D. C., Feb. 7\u2014From!\nevery section of the country, farm 1\nleaders are directing protests to the j\nnation\u2019s capital over the threat to\nfood production which looms on the\nhorizon as a result of the steel\nstrike. The majority strongly urges j\nprompt Congressional action in reg-\nulating the labor monopolies that\nhave paralyzed production.\nFour war years have seen over-1\nworked faim machinery and equip\nment deteriorate to a point where\nin many instances hay wire is being\nused to hold it together. These ru\nral leaders and their constituents\nwant to know why they should go\non producing bumper crops for all\nthe world, while excessive wage de\nmands of CIO strikers tie up the\nmachinery and equipment vitally\nnecessary to plant, cultivate and\nharvest the crops. Thes e same farm\nfolk fear the whirlwind of inflation\nshould industrial wages go skyrock\neting 30 per cent at a clip, followed\nclosely by price increases for things\nthe farmers buy.\nA s one State farm leader put it:\n\u201cFarmers went all out to produce\nthe food and fiber needed to win the\nwar. They are planning to, and will,\nif possoble, produce another bumper\ncrop this year as their contribution\nto reconversion. They are ready to\ngo. even though the labor and ma\nchinery prospects are no brighter\nthan they were last year and there\nare also no prospects of a 30 per\ncent increase in the price of farm\nproducts. If such an attitude pre\nvailed in all economic groups, our\nreconversion problem would soon be j\nover.\u201d\nW. G. Wysor, general manager of j\nSouthern State s Cooperative at Rich- j\nmond, Va.. says: \u201cOs course, every\nbody is gravely concerned over the j\nsteel strike. If it continues any)\nlength of time half the industry of\nthe country will be shut down and\nlour reconversion program will be\nwrecked. In addition, the strike in\nthis basic industry increases the in\nflationary pressures which are al\nready appalling. It seems to me the\nreally basic issue is whether we shall\ncontinue our free enterprise system,\nunder which America has become\nthe most powerful nation on earth\nwith the best standard of living in\nthe world, or operate our economy\nunder some form of statism. We\ncertainly shall not have a free en\nterprise system if the Government\nmakes the decisions as to how much\nthe worker may have, how much the\nowners of a business may earn on\ntheir investment, and what the con\nsumer may have. The Government\nis trying to make these decisions.\nIt frightens me and, I think, a great\nmany other people.\u201d\nW. A. Hambright, master of the\nSouth Carolina Grange, states: \u201cThe\nsteel strike and other industrial\nstrikes are giving farmers in South\nCarolina much concern, and this deep\nconcern is by no means limited to\nfarmers. The success of our farm\nprogram depends upon the produc\ntion of certain repair parts, equip\nment and farm machinery, which\ncannot roll off th e assembly line as\nlong as the steel strike is in effect.\n\u201cWe arc wondering just how much\nthose who are leading the strike\nreally appreciate America as it ex\nists today. Now that the war is\nwon, people would like to settle down\nto work in peace and not be clam\nored with all this fuss between la\nbor and management.\nM. E. Siebert, retiring Master of\nthe Oklahoma State Grange, says:\n\u201cIn general the farmers are up in\nthe air concerning strikes. We have\ndone our best for the winning of\nthis war, with little complaint while\nthe war was on. We were greatly\nhandicapped for lack of machinery\nand parts. We worked twice the\nhours that labor did without time\nand a half. We wanted to win the\nwar and were looking forward to\na great reconversion plan and pro\ngram. Now, see what we have! We\nfeel that these strikes will have a\nvery serious after-effect on agricul\nture as we will not have enough ma\nchinery or parts to produce the re\nquired food and fiber.\u201d\nIt is becoming more evident every\nday to competent observers here in\nWashington that, unless reasonable\nsettlements are quickly arrived at on\nthe strike front, rural America, j\nwhere 53 per cent of our population\nlives, is going to know 1 the reason\nwhy.\nDriver Uses Milk To\nPut Out Truck Fire\nLong Beach, Cal. Tony Freese\nhad a quick decision to make when\nhis truck caught fire in Long Beach,\nCalif. He had a load of 21-hundred\npounds of butter and thirty gallons\nof milk. After a moment\u2019s reflec\ntion on the scarcity of butter and\nthe comparative abundance of milk,\nhe used the milk to put out the fire.\nEverything in the feed line has be\ncome so tightly bound by trading\nthat manufacturers are bartering\nfuriously for most of the protein\nused.\nand. This keeps the wool from i\nhaving a hard-pressed look.\nIt is a good idea to be particular j\nabout the cloths used for pressing, j\nWhen using new material for this j\nmrpose, wash and rinse it thor- j\noughly so that not a bit of starch\n>r sizing remains. Keep the cloths 1\nclean always and wash out every\ntrace of scorch, if by any chance the i\niron gets too hot. A scorched cloth\ncan discolor the garment underneath.\nN.C. State College\nAnswers Timely\nFarm Questions\nQ. Is it safe to use regular caps 1\nand fuses with the type of dynamite I\n(50 per cent nitro-glycerine) now I\nbeing used for ditch blasting in the\nstate?\nA. It is definitely unsafe to use'\nregular caps and fuses with this\ntype of explosive. A blasting ma\nchine not only is time-saver but also\nis tlie safest method of setting off\ncharges.\nQ. What is the best method of\ntransplanting Nandinas?\nA. Nandinas, best transplanted\nsometime during February or early\nMarch, should be lifted with as much\ndirt as possible, care being taken\nnot t 0 injure the mother plant. If\nplants are no more than 10 to 15\ninches high at the time of trans\nplanting. no pruning should be nec\nessary. If, however, the plants are\ntwo to three feet high and only a\nsmall quantity of dirt may be lifted\nwith them, .they should be pruned\nto a height of 12 to 15 inches.\nJ. What are the more likely mar\nkets for North Carolina black wal\nnut timber?\nA. Logs in carload lots may usu\nally be sold to the Carolina Veneer\nCompany of High Point, the Pulaski\nVeneer Company of Pulaski, Va., the\nRedmond Lumber Company of Rich\nmond, Va., or the Wood Mosiac Com\npany of Louisville, Ky. If you have\nbut a small quantity of timber, it is\nsuggested that it be sawed into lum\nber and used locally.\nQ. What are the prospects for\ngetting new farm machinery this\nyear\nA. Not too bright. The actual\nproduction of new farming imple\nmnnts during th<> last three months\nof 1945, a peacetime period, was ap\nproximately 10 per cent less than in\nthe last quarter of 1944, a war pe\nriod, Extension Service specialists\nreport.\nQ. What are the rates of pay\nment to be made under the 1946\nAAA program for seeding Winter\ncover crops?\nA. State AAA men report the\nfollowing rates of pay for cover\ncrops seeded with inoculated seed in\nwell-prepared seedbeds; Crimson clo\nver, 15 cents per pound: hairy vetch.\n12 cents per pound; Austrian winter\npeas, 5 cents per pound, and annual\nrye-glass, 8 cents per pound.\nQ. I\u00ab it really better to prepare\ntobacco plantbeds in the Fall?\nA. Extension Service tobacco spe\ncialists say positively \u201cyes.\u201d Farm\ners who prepared beds last Fall and\napplied cyanamid and uramon to\nkill weeds, though delayed now by\nwet weather in planting seed, are\nfar ahead of farmers who must pre\npare beds from scratch.\nEleanor Roosevelt says in her col\numn that Russia never started a war.\nShe ought to tell that one to the\nFinns.\n9 REASONS for Bringing Your\nPrescriptions to\nLincoln Cut-Rate Drugs.\n1. BECAUSE 4. BECAUSE 7. BECAUSE\nwfn e \u2019ho y fi*lfed P evle^lo ti0 n The selected location of Our Prescription Depart\nyour doctor ordera by Pr eri ,i n \u201c\u2022J\" mot. with it. deadline,*\nprofessional pharmacist, men away rom busy and -high standard of\nlong-schooled and with merchandising, permits practice, has the good\nseasoned experience. Quiet, uninterrupted at- will 0 f the doctors.\ntention to your prescrip\n2. BECAUSE 8. BECAUSE\nment is clean, modern and 5. BECAUSE Our prices on prescrip\nup-to-date in every re- tions are as low as is con\nspect with shelves \u201cbrim r well-defined, umver- professional\nfull\u2019\u2019 of nationally known sal and unvarying system tn Professional\nproducts, including the of procedure in filling ev- service and the use of fine\nlatest discoveries in naedi- ery prescription assures pharmaceuticals, drugs\nClne you of complete accuracy. and chemicals.\n3. BECAUSE 6. BECAUSE 9. BECAUSE\nh,g' S prlsc rn rip o tiof ePl s e toSs Every prescription, before Every prescription fi)led\nfrequently assures you of ls 18 delivered to you, is j st fi\nfresh, pure, up-to-the- carefully double-checked r 8 ed by a\nminute pharmaceuticals to verify its correctness\u2014 registered druggist,\nof famous qualities. an added safeguard.\nLINCOLN CUT-RATE DRUGS, Inc.\nPhone 17 WALGREEN AGENCY Lincolnton, N. C.\nTHE TIMES LEADS IN CIRCULATION, ADVERTISING AND NEWS\nI \u201cSocial Register\u201d\nPlanned For Hogs\nI Declaring that the only \u201creal\"\nmeans of determining the sow\u2019s pro- j\nj ductivity is in the keeping of a \u201cpro\nliuction register,\u201d Jack Kelley, ani-1\nI- imal husbantiryman of the Stale\nCollege Extension Service, urges all\nstate swine producers to keep a rec\nord of litters produced, weight\nj gained by pigs and the number ol\nI pigs in each litter, indicating that\nj efficient production of hogs will re\nsult.\nInasmuch as prolificacy, milking\nability and rate of weight gain by\npigs are all characteristics inherited\nby litters from the mother animal, j\nKelley says, a careful record of the\nsow\u2019s performance will tell the farm\ner and researchers whether that hog\nand associated strains should be\nkept in production. Less profitable\nanimals may be discarded and more\nproductive strains introduced, it was\nadded.\nIn the past, Kelley says, \u201cbrood\n1 sows have been selected on the basis\n1 of body conformation which does\nnot give a true picture of the sow\u2019s\nability to raise large litters of fast\ngrowing pigs. Breeders have often\nbeen disappointed upon buying a\nhigh-priced sow which failed to pro\nduce.\u201d\n1 Cards for nominating litters of\npigs for the \u201csocial register\u201d can be\nnotices]\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nHaving this day qualified as ex\necutor of the last will and testament\nof J. T. Houser, deceased, late of\nLincoln County, North Carolina, this\n1 is t 0 notify all creditors of the de\nceased to file their claims with the\ni undersigned on or before the 22nd\nday of January, 1947, or this no\ni tice will be pleaded in bar of recov\nery.\nThis the 19th day of January,\n1946.\nCarl Daniel Houser, Executor.\nVale, North Carolina.\nJONAS JONAS, Attorneys.\n6t-l-21\nADMINISTRATOR\u2019S NOTICE\nThe undersigned having this day\nqualified as the Administrator of\nMrs. Mary M. McMurray, deceased.\nlate of Lincoln County, N. C., all\npersons holding claims against the\nsaid estate will kindly present them\nproperly sworn to and itemized, to\nthe undersigned or his attorney, on\nor before th e 23rd day of January,\n1947, or this notice will be pleaded\nin bar of recovery. All persons\nowing said estate will please call aiu.\nsettle at once.\nWitness my hand, this January 23.\n1946.\nA. Y. McMURRAY,\nAdministrator Mary M.\nMcMurray, deceased.\nKemp B. Nixon. Attorney,\nLincolnton, N. C.\n6t\u201424, 31, 7, 14, 21, 28.\nTwo Maine Hog Siorieaj\n(Lisbon, Me., Enterprise) j\nBill French killed a hog last week.:\nand it weighed 530 pounds after\nbeing dressed\u2014or undressed. A lot\nof people have been trying to figure\nout what it must have cost, in these\ndays of gold-plated hog feeds, to\nput 530 pounds on a hog, and have\nconcluded that while that weight is\nsomething Bill can be extra proud of,\nit is even more phenomenal now\nthan it would have been 20 years\nago.\nFor some reason it makes us think\nof the story somebody told us once\nabout Jim Knight and the hog he\ngot Harry Davis to stick for him.\nJim is supposed to have called Har\nry and said he would pay him $5\nif he would do the job on a Sunday, i\nand as mo\u00ab*. gigs were going around\n200 or two-and-quarter in those days,\nit sounded like a good proposition,\nbecause the going price was a cent\nobtained by the producer from breed\nassociations and the entry must be\nmade within five days after farrow\ning time. If a little so entered\nreaches the required 56-day weight\nof 320 pounds, it automatically qual\nj ifies as a \u201cProduction Registry\u201d lit\nter.\nIs,! To the Boy Scouts on the cele\nbration of their 36th Anniver-\nThe Boy Scouts of today\nWr iMV our leaders of tomorrow. Let\u2019s\njPPflf give them our full co-opera-\nW W LINCOLN HARDWARE\nM Mk. COMPANY\nPhone 237 Lincolnton\n.1 pound. Harry, the story goes,\nfigured he'd make about extia.\nAnyway Harry\u2019s folks were going\nor* on Sunday, and he was going to\nbe home alone, and he didn't have\nmiyih.ng else to do, so he said r.i\nright and told Jim to show up with\nihe hog around 0 o\u2019clock. Jim did,\nand he had a hog that weighed Sad\npounds net W'hich lie claimed he\u2019 l\nraised on cucumbers and table scrap.\nAnyway, instead of getting $8.30\nfor killing the hog, Harry got the $o\nand said he\u2019d learned a valuable les\nson.\nThe world carry-over of cotton\nstands at 26.5 million bales as com\npared with 22 million bales before\nthe war.\nTRUCK FOR HIRE\nSee\nRALPH SHIDAL\nAt\nBangle\u2019s Esso Service Station\nPhone 9111","height":"20372","width":"15098"}}
